{"parse":{"title":"A Short History of Byzantium","pageid":30825492,"revid":822610809,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>A Short History of Byzantium</b></i> (1997) is a history of the <a href=\"/wiki/Byzantine_Empire\" title=\"Byzantine Empire\">Byzantine Empire</a> by historian <a href=\"/wiki/John_Julius_Norwich\" title=\"John Julius Norwich\">John Julius Norwich</a>. It is a condensed version of his earlier three-volume work on the same subject, published from 1988 to 1995 in 1200 pages, which is approximately one page per year of historical time covered.\n</p><p>Norwich's thesis (as stated in the introduction) is that Byzantium left behind a rich legacy, both as a cultural powerhouse and as a bulwark protecting Western Europe against  invaders like the <a href=\"/wiki/Sasanian_Empire\" title=\"Sasanian Empire\">Sasanian Empire</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Arab_Caliphate\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arab Caliphate\">Arab Caliphate</a>. The history of the Empire is considered in its entirety, from the reign of <a href=\"/wiki/Constantine_the_Great\" title=\"Constantine the Great\">Constantine the Great</a> to the <a href=\"/wiki/Fall_of_Constantinople\" title=\"Fall of Constantinople\">Fall of Constantinople</a> in 1453 AD. Historical events like the <a href=\"/wiki/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire\" title=\"Fall of the Western Roman Empire\">Fall of the Western Roman Empire</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Byzantine_Iconoclasm\" title=\"Byzantine Iconoclasm\">Byzantine Iconoclasm</a>, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Crusades\" title=\"Crusades\">Crusades</a> are discussed. The various palace coups and court intrigues involving the emperors and their families are also covered. Lists of reigning emperors, sultans, and popes are provided in the appendixes.\n</p><p>The condensed version was published by Viking originally in London, then by Knopf in New York.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=A_Short_History_of_Byzantium&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/04/27/bib/970427.rv105101.html/\"><i>A Short History of Byzantium</i></a>- As reviewed by Michael Anderson in <i>The New York Times Book Review</i></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.vintagenovels.com/2015/01/a-short-history-of-byzantium-by-john.html\"><i>A Short History of Byzantium</i></a>-As reviewed by Suzannah Rowntree in Vintage Novels</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Europe_green_light.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Europe green light.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Europe_green_light.svg/32px-Europe_green_light.svg.png\" width=\"32\" height=\"28\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Europe_green_light.svg/48px-Europe_green_light.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Europe_green_light.svg/64px-Europe_green_light.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"260\" data-file-height=\"226\" /></a><img alt=\"Hourglass drawing.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Hourglass_drawing.svg/22px-Hourglass_drawing.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"29\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Hourglass_drawing.svg/33px-Hourglass_drawing.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Hourglass_drawing.svg/44px-Hourglass_drawing.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"546\" data-file-height=\"708\" /></td><td><i>This article about a non-fiction book on European history is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can he